Yes, let‚Äôs talk about the üêò in the room. The British made coffee commercial in 1820, and since then production has been diluted into private establishments overseen by the Indian coffee board. What if coffee was never commercialized by British? My ‚ù§Ô∏è for coffee has changed.

Thousands of families‚Äô livelihoods depend on coffee plantations. Planters have their own song for cherry picking season üòä All this coffee production is managed by the Indian ministry of commerce i.e. under-valued labor. https://t.co/Tohwa2n1tn

The best grade coffee (AAA) grown here in these hills is exported to Europe. What we drink in India is ‚Äòfilter coffee,‚Äô which is at best third grade. The ingredient ‚Äòchircory‚Äô is added to Indian coffee to make it less bitter. Coffee exported to Europe is pure, chicory-free. https://t.co/clcOeBLaxC

The fact that coffee is shade grown means incredible bio-diversity. Fruit-bearing trees around coffee feed üêòüê¶ ü¶ãand other insects. In fact, üêú termite hills are an indicator of soil quality and grasshoppers  eating coffee leaves indicate üëå coffee quality!

There‚Äôs two specialities about this Indian coffee. (1) it‚Äôs shade grown (2) high elevation of 2000m. In fact, Indian coffee planters (of avg height 5ft) limit the height of the plant to their own height, so they can easily pluck the cherries. https://t.co/kcADKU1Jnd

Arab traders brought coffee back to their homeland. In 17th century, Baba Budan, on his trip to Mecca, stole some coffee beans and brought it to a coffee-less India in Chikmagalur. Now there‚Äôs a mountain in his name, and a religious house where both Hindus and Muslims pray.

...we owe the discovery of coffe to goats? In 850BC, a shepherd in the Ethiopian highlands noticed that his goat became hyperactive after eating some coffee plant cherriesüçí. He tried it himself, noticing the same effects. It soon became a closely guarded ‚Äòmagical‚Äô secret.
